---

<InternWiki title={title} description={description} category={category} order={order}>
	<h2>Institutional Housing Infrastructure</h2>
	<p>University dormitories provide the most reliable and scam-proof housing infrastructure for summer interns. Institutions convert their vacant student housing into short-term rentals from late May through early August. This eliminates the need for guarantors, broker fees, and stressful sublet negotiations.</p>
	
	<h3>Key Providers</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>New York University (NYU):</strong> NYU offers extensive summer housing in prime Downtown Manhattan locations like Union Square and Washington Square Park. Applications open in February and fill quickly. You do not need to be an NYU student to apply.</li>
		<li><strong>Educational Housing Services (EHS):</strong> EHS operates private student residences across Manhattan and Brooklyn. They partner with major corporations to house intern cohorts together. They provide furnished rooms, 24-hour security, and immediate community access.</li>
		<li><strong>Columbia University:</strong> Columbia offers summer housing in Morningside Heights. This location requires a longer commute to Midtown or Wall Street but offers a quieter residential environment and lower costs.</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Cost Analysis</h2>
	<p>Dormitory housing requires full upfront payment before move-in. While the monthly rate is comparable to market rent, you avoid paying a security deposit, broker fee, or utility setup charges. Rooms are fully furnished and include high-speed internet and air conditioning. Shared rooms cost significantly less than private singles.</p>
</InternWiki>
